\par }\pard\plain \qj\fi284 \f2\lang2057 {\f6 
\par }{\f6 The Color Editor is called every time colors are assigned and displays a window named "Resource Color Viewer" which contains 12 (max) configured colors.
\par }\pard \qj {\b \{bmc mi_cores.bmp\}
\par }\pard \qj\fi284 {\f6 Every color can be selected by clicking on the button which contains the desired color; the adjacent text field contains the string defining the color.
\par }{\f6 Through the Edit pulldown menu the user can call the "Color Editor" to build a new color}{\f6 , to display the active Colormap or by selecting "Grab color" to import a new one (for example  from the color map).
\par }{\f6 
\par }{\f6 It is possible to change a default color from the default palette by following these steps:
\par }{\f6 1) select the desired color on the default palette;
\par }{\f6 2) modify the color either through the Color Editor or by writing the color string in the text field or grabbing a color;
\par }{\f6 3) press the "Apply" push button;
\par }{\f6 4) select a second time the button color of the palette;
\par }{\f6 The new default color palette }{\f6 will be saved in a local file named FileColoriDefault after pressing "OK". This file will be loaded every time the Color viewer is used.
\par }{\f6 
\par }{\f6 
The definition of a new color by the Color Editor is made by dragging the mouse on the red, green and blue scrolling bars. Once the user has pressed "OK" the new color will be exported in the Color Viewer, the display will be possible after pressing "Appl
}{\f6 y" in the "Color Viewer".
\par }{\f6 
\par }{\f6 After pressing a color inside an application windows the user can select "Grab color" to}{\f6  capture the color of the point  and load it in the Color Viewer.
\par }{\f6 
\par }{\f6 The Color Map displays the available color of the active colormap. Every color can be captured by using "Grab Color".
\par }{\f6 
\par }\pard \qj\fi284\sl240 {\f6 The Color Editor and the Color Map windows are available in:
